Lebesgue integration numerically is usually best thought of as approximating the measure of value-level sets or approximating the function by simple functions, not just as “sum weights × samples.” That is a different mindset from classical Riemann-style quadrature.

A few useful families:

1. Simple-function approximation You replace  by a step function of the form

s(x)=\sum_{k=1}^m a_k\,\mathbf 1_{E_k}(x),

\int f\,d\mu \approx \sum_{k=1}^m a_k\,\mu(E_k).

For a nonnegative function, a common version is:

f(x)\approx \sum_{j=1}^m \Delta t \,\mathbf 1_{\{f(x)>j\Delta t\}},

\int f\,d\mu \approx \Delta t \sum_{j=1}^m \mu(\{f>j\Delta t\}).

This is called a layer-cake or superlevel-set approximation.

2. Layer-cake / distribution-function methods For ,

\int f\,d\mu=\int_0^\infty \mu(\{x:f(x)>t\})\,dt.

Numerically, this can be very effective when:

the function has sharp spikes,

the geometry of the level sets is easier to estimate than the pointwise integral,

you only care about the distribution of function values.


This is especially useful in image processing, statistics, and PDEs, where thresholded sets are easy to compute.

3. Partition-of-range methods Instead of subdividing the domain into cells, you subdivide the output values:

choose thresholds ,

estimate the measure of each slice ,

approximate


\int f\,d\mu \approx \sum_{j=1}^m c_j\,\mu(\{t_{j-1}<f\le t_j\}),

This is often more “Lebesgue-like” than grid quadrature.

4. Histogram-based integration If you sample the domain and build a histogram of , then the integral can be approximated by

\int f\,d\mu \approx \sum_j \text{bin center}_j \times \text{estimated mass of bin}_j.

This is good when you want:

robustness to irregular geometry,

approximate integrals of complicated random fields,

a distributional view of the integral.


5. Monte Carlo integration This is not just “weighting” in the quadrature sense; it is a measure-theoretic estimator:

\int f\,d\mu \approx \frac1N\sum_{i=1}^N f(X_i)

It is especially good when:

dimension is high,

the domain is complicated,

deterministic grids become expensive.


Variance reduction techniques matter a lot here, but the core idea is still Lebesgue-friendly: you are averaging with respect to the measure.

6. Stratified and adaptive sampling Instead of plain Monte Carlo, split the domain into measurable strata , then sample inside each stratum:

\int f\,d\mu = \sum_{k=1}^m \int_{A_k} f\,d\mu.

7. Rearrangement-based methods If you know or can estimate the decreasing rearrangement , then

\int f\,d\mu = \int_0^{\mu(X)} f^\*(s)\,ds.

8. Adaptive measurable-set refinement This is a hybrid of simple-function approximation and adaptive meshing:

start with a coarse partition of the domain,

estimate variation of  on each cell,

subdivide only where needed,

approximate  by constants on each measurable cell.


This works well when  has localized complexity. It feels like finite elements, but the emphasis is on approximating measurable sets and simple functions rather than smooth interpolants.


