A practical way to think about it

If you do not like “weighting,” then Lebesgue-style numerical integration can be organized around these three viewpoints:

1. Approximate the function by simple functions.


2. Approximate the measure of level sets.


3. Approximate the distribution of function values.



Those are often more natural than classical quadrature when the function is discontinuous, spiky, or defined on a weird measurable set.

When these beat standard quadrature

They are often preferable when:

the integrand is highly discontinuous,

the domain has complicated geometry,

the dimension is large,

the function’s level sets are easier to understand than pointwise behavior.


A nice rule of thumb:
if the problem is “how much of the space has values around this range?” then a Lebesgue-based numerical method is usually the right lens.

